title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.1: COMMUNITY BEHAVIOUR CHANGE - REDUCED MORTALITY & STUNTING

description.narrative: Output 1.1: In 10 or more disadvantaged counties, communities increasingly have improved service-seeking behaviour and adopt desirable practices on sanitation and water use, young child feeding and parenting, maternity and prevention of child disease and HIV/AIDS, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 1 - Reduced Mortality & Stunting: Increased proportions of vulnerable children, pregnant and lactating women, including adolescent girls, have equitable access to and use quality Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH), Nutrition, Health and HIV/AIDS services to reduce their risk of mortality, preventable diseases, stunting and other forms of malnutrition, and improve their birth outcomes.

title.narrative: Output 1.1: In 10 or more disadvantaged counties, communities increasingly have improved service-seeking behaviour and adoptdesirable practices on sanitation and water use, young child feeding and parenting, maternity and prevention of child disease andHIV/AIDS

description.narrative: Populations in targeted communities are demonstrating improved service-seeking behaviours and utilization of integrated preventive health services, including uptake;of ideal practices related to water and sanitation, maternal newborn and child health, HIV, and nutrition. As a result, 3,384 villages were certified as Open Defecation Free, and 80.1 per cent;of targeted women received Iron Folic Acid Supplementation. Other;achievements include the implementation of the Primary Health Care Strategic Framework, the approval of the Breastmilk Substitutes regulations, and the development of the community PMTCT training curriculum with 2,120 (1340 males,780 females) community HIV champions and 480 pregnant adolescent and young mothers trained. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:05/01/2022
